riginal intent of driving out to Montana with a stranger, the idea was to save money.  Did I accomplish this?  Between the hotel room (50% of $60) the gas, and the food, I figure I spent at least $170.  I was generous with my gas money contributions to George because let’s face it; he provided door to door service and assumed all of the wear and tear on his vehicle, plus he did all of the driving.  The absolute cheapest airfare I could find was $219-$325 each way, depending upon the date chosen (round trip airfares were equally or more expensive).  So I did save some money, not a huge amount, but I got an experience too.  Nine days later, after a great time in Bozeman, I flew home.  I thought it was kind of strange how flying took me so quickly from one place to another, there was no real transition.  The driving experience was more impressive, it provided a sense of just how big and diverse this country is.    I realized that our society has sacrificed certain aspects of the life experience for the sake of speed and the notion that time is money.  While speed and timeliness are important aspects of our contemporary lifestyles, sometimes we lose a bit of what is good in life by being hectic.  Sometimes it is good to go slowly.

Note: names of people in this story have been changed to protect their privacy
